# Prefer gh for GitHub Operations

Use the GitHub CLI (`gh`) for all GitHub-specific operations. Avoid hand-crafted `curl` calls or parsing `git remote` output when `gh` provides a purpose-built subcommand.

## Rules

1. Use `gh pr`, `gh issue`, `gh run`, `gh repo`, and `gh release` subcommands as the first choice.
2. Fall back to `gh api <endpoint>` only when no dedicated subcommand covers the operation (e.g. resolving a review thread, reading CODEOWNERS via API).
3. When GitHub MCP tools are configured, prefer MCP for reading PR comments, listing issues, and fetching repo metadata over parsing `gh` text output.
4. Never write raw `curl` calls to `api.github.com` unless `gh api` is explicitly unavailable.

## Examples

```bash
# ❌ BAD — manual curl to list PRs
curl -H "Authorization: token $GH_TOKEN" \
  https://api.github.com/repos/owner/repo/pulls

# ✅ GOOD — use gh subcommand
gh pr list --state open

# ❌ BAD — parse git remote to get PR checks
git remote -v | grep origin | ...

# ✅ GOOD — use gh directly
gh pr checks
```

```bash
# gh api is acceptable when no subcommand exists
gh api repos/{owner}/{repo}/pulls/{pull_number}/comments
```
